<subSubSection id="C3012FA2FFE60C0BBDC9216CCCEE3FBF" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA47C29FFE60C0BBDC9216CCCEE3FBF" blockId="1.[151,1437,1446,1761]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">
<emphasis id="B96FA03BFFE60C0BBDC9216CCF613F73" bold="true" box="[199,315,1555,1581]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Remarks.</emphasis>
Based on a molecular analysis by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A01D8FFE60C0BBFCF216CCDF13F73" author="Sigwart, J. D. &amp; Schwabe, E. &amp; Saito, H. &amp; Samadi, S. &amp; Giribet, G." box="[705,939,1555,1581]" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" pagination="560 - 572" refId="ref18930" refString="Sigwart, J. D., Schwabe, E., Saito, H., Samadi, S. &amp; Giribet, G. (2010) Evolution in the deep sea: a combined analysis of the earliest diverging living chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora: Lepidopleurida). Invertebrate Systematics, 24, 560 - 572. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / IS 10028" type="journal article" year="2010">Sigwart et al. (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B07AAFFE60C0BB927216CCAF53F73" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[1065,1199,1555,1581]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96FA03BFFE60C0BB927216CCAF53F73" box="[1065,1199,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Leptochiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not monophyletic. Morphological studies of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B07AAFFE60C0BBF202148CCEE3F0F" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[558,692,1591,1617]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96FA03BFFE60C0BBF202148CCEE3F0F" box="[558,692,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Leptochiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed some groups of species that possess a set of similar features, which include the shell, girdle, radula, and gills. Most of these groups inhabit a more or less restricted area, but several groups, mainly of deep-water leptochitons, are widely distributed in the world oceans. Probably the first species of each of these groups originated from different ancestors of the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B07AAFFE60C0BB93C21DCCAB23FE3" authorityName="Dall" authorityYear="1889" box="[1074,1256,1699,1725]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Leptochitonidae</taxonomicName>
resulting in the polyphyletic character of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B07AAFFE60C0BBF2621B8CCF43FBF" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[552,686,1735,1761]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="1" pageNumber="402" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96FA03BFFE60C0BBF2621B8CCF43FBF" box="[552,686,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="402">Leptochiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
